source:
<Bold>Weekly Checkup: 1172</>

Week ending 12/23/94

<widget id="Line"/>

Subject: 1172

<widget id="Line"/>

Original Procedure Date: 11/90

<widget id="Line"/>

Reason(s) for Observation:

- Emotional dysregulation

- Overactive autonomic nervous system (acute stress response)

- Episodes consisting of shaking, heavy breathing, and decreased concentration

<widget id="Line"/>

Observations:

When given writing implements, 1172 has communicated (to the best of her ability) high levels of stress, feelings of impending doom, and a strong desire to return to her previous living quarters. These reported feelings (and  accompanying symptoms) began following 1172’s transfer to The Shelf, and originally rendered her unable to complete assigned tasks.

Recently, however, 1172 has shown gradual but steady improvements. Research staff have noted a drop in number of emotional episodes, as well as shortened duration when they do occur. One factor for this improvement is believed to be scheduled periods of supervised socialization with other subjects within the block. This measure was personally requested by Stella Greyber, and has had a positive impact not only on 1172, but several other subjects.

Subject continues to rub the fur on her arms, most likely unconsciously in response to stress.

<widget id="Line"/>

Conclusion:

At this rate, it’s believed 1172 will not need corrective intervention (medical or otherwise) after all. While still reporting negative feelings, subject is back to a state of functioning such that she can return to her tasks. For the time being, the research team recommends physical work in a quiet setting.

[    ] Waitlist for Corrective Procedure(s)
[    ] No Change
[ X ] Transfer Out

<widget id="Line"/>

<Italic>To be filled by department head</>

Transfer Destination: Storage B

Department: Production
target:
<Bold>每周检查:1172</>

截止至1994年12月23日的周报

<widget id="Line"/>

对象:1172

<widget id="Line"/>

最初手术日期:1990年11月

<widget id="Line"/>

观察原因:

- 情绪失调

- 自主神经系统过度活跃（急性应激反应）

- 呈现颤抖、呼吸急促和注意力下降的发作症状

<widget id="Line"/>

观察报告:

当提供书写工具时，1172（尽其所能）表达了极度的压力、末日即将到来的感觉，以及想要返回之前住处的强烈愿望。这些报告的情绪（及伴随症状）始于1172被转移到The Shelf之后，最初使其无法完成分配的任务。

然而，最近1172表现出逐渐但稳定的好转。研究人员注意到情绪发作的次数减少，发作持续时间也缩短了。这改善的一个因素被认为是定时安排与其他受试者的监管社交时间。这一措施是Stella Greyber亲自提出的，不仅对1172，还对其他几位受试者产生了积极的影响。

对象继续摩擦手臂上的毛皮，很可能是无意识中对压力的反应。

<widget id="Line"/>

结论:

按此进展速度，可以认为1172最终将不需要进行矫正干预（无论是药物还是其他方式）。虽然仍报告有负面情绪，但受试者已经恢复到可以继续完成任务的功能状态。目前，研究团队建议在安静的环境中进行体力工作。

source:
Prototype’s been finding ways past the traps. Don’t know how. Have to keep changing the setups to keep him away.

He was <Italic>right outside</> the door last night. Just staring and tapping at the wall. All I can think about since is that clanking of metal, those spidery legs, <Italic>that face</>.

We’ve double checked every entrance, made sure this place is good and locked down. Still, who knows how long these defenses will last. We’re completely surrounded now. All sides, even above and below. Nowhere left to run to, no place left to hide; end of the line.
target:
原型体找到了绕过陷阱的方法。不知道是怎么做到的。必须不断改变布局才能将它挡在外面。

昨晚它就在门<Italic>外头</>。只是站在那里盯着，用肢体敲打墙壁。自那以后我就满脑子都是那金属的哐当作响声，那些像蜘蛛腿一样的肢体，还有<Italic>那张脸</>。

我们已反复检查了每个入口，确认这个地方已被严密封锁。然而，这些防御措施能撑多久谁也说不准。我们现在已经被完全包围了，四面八方，甚至上下都被封锁。再也没有地方可逃，无处可藏；死路一条。

source:
<Bold>Behavior:</>
Much like its predecessors, 1163 displays none of the typical human qualities. Whatever’s left of the “bright, joyful, bundle of laughter” (Per the Counselor’s report) appears limited, or altogether depleted. A shame, I suppose.  

I grow tired of creating mindless invalids. 1160 had his uses, but 1163 lacks the cunning or the size for a similar role. And that’s not what the Initiative is about anyway. 

1163’s temperment is like that of a rabid animal. It snaps at perceived motion, eats whatever fits in its mouth regardless of appetite, combats the conditioning staff, and it CANNOT even play its insipid piano rhythms in TUNE (perhaps one of the others from its line would have presented better music). Had any of these actions been a result of conscious thought, perhaps I would be intrigued.  

I am not intrigued. 

<Bold>Conclusion:</>
Use 1163 for testing. If it survives, keep it there. However, I don’t expect it to. 

This Initiative will produce no more experiments such as this. Measurable improvements have to be made. Otherwise, I will have to re-evaluate the effectiveness of those in my perview. 

<Bold>Signature:</>
Dr. Harley Sawyer
target:
<Bold>行为:</>
与其前身类似，1163并未展现出任何典型的人类特质。根据顾问报告，「那个聪明、快乐、笑声不断的家伙」所剩无几（若还有的话）。真遗憾啊，我想。

我厌倦了制造没有思维的废物。1160有它的用途，但1163既没有狡猾的头脑，也缺乏足够体型来承担类似的角色。况且，那也并非我们计划的目标。

1163的性情如同一只疯狗。它会扑向任何察觉到的动作，不考虑饥饿与否，把任何能塞进嘴里的东西都吞下去，还会攻击训练人员，甚至连它那该死的钢琴节拍都弹不准（也许它同类里的其他个体还能弹出点像样的音乐）。如果它的这些行为是出于有意识的思考结果，也许我还会有点兴趣。

然而，我并不感兴趣。

<Bold>结论:</>
将1163用于测试。如果它能活下来，就留着它。但我不认为它能。

这个计划不会再继续产生这样的试验品了。必须进行显著改进。否则，我就得重新评估我手下某些成员的能力了。

<Bold>签名:</>
哈雷·索耶博士

source:
“Being chosen.” The other kids talk about it a lot. I still don’t know what that’s about exactly. If it means being adopted, I’m not sure I even want that. 

What’s important to me:
-Figuring out if I even want to be adopted.
-Trying to feel what the other kids seem to feel day in and day out. 

Why:
If I was happy like them and could feel it like that, maybe I’d appreciate everything more. Maybe I’d want to be chosen too.   

<widget id="Line"/>

February 10th, 1995  

I’ve been chosen. Dr. White chose me. 

For a while, I didn’t know I wanted to be, or how I’d feel if I was. But, really, I think I’m happy! There were interviews, of course, but I didn’t think any of those couples actually liked me. Too anxious. Too quiet. Doesn’t get along with the other kids. And good test scores don’t always make a good kid, they’d often say. But I guess <Italic>somebody</> liked me. 

I asked if I could take my journal. They said yes, but I wanted to write this out before I leave. 

I haven’t felt like this since before the accident. Since my parents. The lists Ms. Harper told me about have helped me a lot in recent months, and now, I think I have more for the first list than ever. 

What’s important to me:
-That I still try to be the girl my parents raised. Live by their values so that a part of them is still here, so that their lives mattered.
-Being good to myself, and to whoever takes me in.
-Staying happy.
-Finding more friends.
-Getting used to a new home.-Growing up to help kids that were like me.
-Start an orphanage, like Elliot Ludwig, and fill it with toys and good people.
target:
「被选中。」其他孩子经常谈论这个。我仍然不太清楚那到底是怎么回事。如果这意味着被收养，我不确定自己是否真的想要那样。

对我来说什么是重要的:
-弄清楚我是否真的想被收养。
-试着感受其他孩子似乎每天都在感受的东西。

为什么:
如果我能像他们一样快乐，并且能那样真切地感受到，也许我会更加珍惜一切。也许我也会想要被选中吧。

<widget id="Line"/>

1995年2月10日

我被选中了。怀特博士选择了我。

有段时间，我不知道自己是否想要被选中，也不知道如果真被选中了，我会有什么感觉。但是，真的，我想我是开心的!当然，之前有过很多面试，但我并不觉得那些夫妇真的喜欢我。太焦虑。太安静。与其他孩子相处不来。而且，他们常常说，好的考试成绩并不代表就是一个好孩子。但我想，还是有<Italic>人</>喜欢我的。

我问过是否可以带着我的日记本。他们说可以，但在离开之前，我想把这段写下来。

自从事故发生前、自从我的父母去世，我就再也没有过这样的感觉了。哈珀女士让我记下的那些清单，在最近几个月对我帮助很大，而现在，我认为第一个清单里又多了一些内容。

对我来说，重要的事情是:
-继续努力做父母养育我时的那个女孩。遵循他们的价值观生活，这样他们的某些部分就依然存在于此，他们的生命也就有了意义。
-善待自己，善待收养我的人。
-保持快乐。
-交到更多朋友。
-适应一个新家。
-长大以后帮助那些像我一样的孩子。
-创办一所像艾略特·路德维希那样的孤儿院，并且里面装满玩具和善良的人。

source:
Elevators?
All shut. Can’t escape. 

Construction Tunnels?
Could lead on forever. Easily lost inside.

Probably has the same freezing traps that No Man’s Land does. Can’t do that to Doey. He’s all that keeps us safe. Doctor knew that when he had them planted.

<Bold>Cell Blocks</> –
<Strikethrough>North</> - The worst of the worst there. Doc uses that. Nowhere for us there.

<Strikethrough>East</> - Guard station and barriers appear intact. Strictly within the Doctor’s control, and rabids are everywhere. Lost too many to them already. 

<Strikethrough>Northeast</> - The doors on all sides are barricaded. All my usual tricks can’t get me in. Feels… off.

<Strikethrough>West</> - Skeletons and claw markings in all the cells. Seems people were kept here. After the Hour. Can’t let the littles see this. 

<Strikethrough>Northwest</> - Too many bad memories. We need hope, not hopelessness. 

<Strikethrough>Barracks</> - Might run on its own emergency power. Security designed to kill us (might be turned off)

It’s a choice between what we KNOW will kill us, and what MIGHT. For me, that’s easy.

Little choice. No path out. Casualties high. Only one place left. I hope we can live with it.

<Bold>牢房区</> –
<Strikethrough>北区</> - 那里是最恶劣的。博士在用那个地方。我们没机会。

<Strikethrough>东区</> - 岗哨和障碍物似乎完好无损。完全在博士的掌控下，而且到处都是狂暴者。已经损失太多人了。

<Strikethrough>东北区</> - 四面的大门都被堵死了。我平时的那些招数全都没用。感觉……不对劲。

<Strikethrough>西区</> - 所有牢房里都有骷髅和爪痕。看来这里关过人。是在「时刻」之后。不能让小孩子们看到这个。

<Strikethrough>西北区</> - 太多糟糕的回忆。我们需要的是希望，而不是绝望。

我们只能在确定会死的地方和可能不会死的地方之间选择。对我来说，这很简单。

没太多选择。没出路。伤亡高。只剩一个地方了。我希望我们能承受得起。

source:
Dr. White,

This letter acts as acknowledgement of your new position, as well as a restatement of your goals and expectations.

As the <Italic>Head of the Secondary Laboratory</>, it will be YOUR responsibility to maintain your staff and adhere to pre-established guidelines. You will present each week’s findings in the Primary Laboratory during our pre-established executive viewing times. You will maintain the pre-established code of conduct regarding company secrets, and ensure ALL under your purview adhere to the self same codes.

I believe, if you’ve the mind your resume infers, that you’re sensing a trend here.

You’ve now seen tragic examples of men who let ego blind them to the Project’s actual goals. Who let perceived personal gain overwhelm good sense. You will be better than this, Dr. White.

For now, the Secondary Lab’s mission is as follows:

Make something useful out of the experiments who won’t cooperate. Rip them open again and again until you’ve salvaged <Italic>something</>. Whatever knowledge you still require, you are to extract it from what remains of Dr. Sawyer. He will fight you, but it will do him no good.  Everything he knows and thinks is only ever a matter of button presses away.

Good luck. And whatever else you may require, reach out to me personally.

With regards,
Eddie M.N. Ritterman
target:
怀特博士，

此信旨在确认您的新职位，同时重申您的目标与期望。

作为<斜体>次级实验室主管</>，您有责任管理员工并遵循预设的指导方针。您将在预设的执行官观看时间，于主实验室中汇报每周的研究成果。您必须遵守关于公司机密的既定行为准则，并确保所有在您监管下的人都严格遵守同样的规范。

我相信，若您具备简历中所体现的头脑，您正在察觉到这一趋势。

您已见证了一些悲剧性的例子：这些人让自我蒙蔽了项目的真实目标，让所谓的个人利益凌驾于常识之上。您将必须做得更好，怀特博士。

目前，次级实验室的使命如下：

就实验对象中不愿配合的部分制造实用成果。一次又一次地剖开他们，直到您获取到<斜体>某些</>东西为止。您仍需要的一切知识，都要从索耶博士的残存中提取。他会反抗您，但这对他没有用。他所有的知识和思维只需要几次按钮按下即可揭晓。

祝好运。如您需要其它任何资源，请亲自与我联系。

此致，
埃迪·M·N·里特曼

source:
For all intent and purposes, Matthew Hallard is a DREAM child. 

He’s thoughtful, kind, considerate, understanding. And while maybe not as intelligent as some of the other children (averaging only B to C level work in School), nor as physically gifted, he MORE than makes up for it in his charm and charisma. 

There’s NOBODY down here who isn’t fond of the boy. It’s just a shame that he came to us already a boy of fifteen, well into his puberty. Most parents look for a child a lot younger. He understands.

Though he rarely speaks on it, I know Matthew suffers from DEEP insecurities. I’ve read the reports on the accident that put him here. He blames himself for the family he couldn’t save. I believe he’s on the road to healing, but the way is long. And <Underline>nobody</> mourns the same. 

He’s become something of a leader to the younger children though, even reading them books LATE into the afternoon (we allow it, sorry). “The Adventures of the Word Wizard” is his favorite. They listen to him when he breaks up fights in the Playhouse, and hang on almost every word he says. And seeing him like this, assuming this role, I think it’s what he needs. Should he age out, I might even request bringing him onto staff.

Signature:
Claire Harper

<widget id="Line"/>

<Italic>(He IS a good candidate for 1322C, should his personality mesh with the other two. But please, be gentle if you pick him. He’s a fine young man. The future we’re fighting for would be a waste if we sacrifice too many like him. -Stella)</>
target:
Matthew Hallard 可以说是一个完美的梦想孩子。

他深思熟虑、善良、体贴、善解人意。虽然在智力上可能不如其他孩子（在学校的成绩只能达到 B 到 C 的水平），身体素质也不算突出，但他凭借迷人的魅力和号召力完全弥补了这些不足。

在这里，没有人不喜欢这个男孩。可惜的是，他来到我们这里时已经十五岁了，正处于青春期。大多数领养者通常会选择更小的孩子。但马修很理解这一点。

尽管他不常提及，但我知道 Matthew 有着深刻的不安全感。我看过关于那场事故的报告——他无法挽救自己的家人，因此深感自责。我相信他正在走向痊愈的路上，但这条路还很漫长。而且，<Underline>每个人</>的悲痛方式都不一样。

然而，他已经成为年幼孩子们的领导者。他甚至会在下午很晚的时候给他们读书（我们也默许了，抱歉）。「词汇巫师的冒险」是他的最爱。当他调解 Playhouse 里的争执时，孩子们都听他的，几乎他说的每一个字都能引起共鸣。当他承担起这个角色时，我认为这就是他所需要的。如果他长大离开这里，我甚至可能申请让他加入员工队伍。

source:
<Bold>Behavior:</>
Characteristic for these early ilk, 1166 demonstrates an acute lack of higher cognitive function. Complex reasoning, speech, problem-solving, and greater introspection all appear either severely limited or altogether nonfunctional. Physically, it’s what it needs to be. Strong. Agile. Swift. And yet I’d hoped for a greater mind behind it. 

However, 1166 displays an odd sense of loyalty to a select few security staff, who nauseatingly feel some kind of sympathy for it, indicative of domesticated dogs and cats. This means its will can be bent. It feels. It fears. 

I believe this is our first sign of progression. That our processes, while admittedly still rudamentary, are showing us where more work need be done, and that improvements ARE possible. Still, 1166, “Yarnaby,” is an odd, funny little creature. The way it sits in the corner and watches me, playing its funny little music (I’m glad this request was taken seriously, I got a good laugh out of it). It amuses me.  

<Bold>Conclusion:</>
I’m going to isolate it. It’ll have contact with no one but me. Considering my importance to the project, it’s doubley important that I’m properly protected at all times. And besides, I might get a good laugh or two at the pathetic little sounds it makes. 

By the time I’m done with it, I’ll be its entire world. It’ll know nothing else. 

<Bold>Signature:</>
Dr. Harley Sawyer
target:
<Bold>行为:</>
这些早期族类的特征在于，1166表现出严重的高级认知功能缺失。复杂推理、语言、解决问题的能力以及更深层次的自我反省，似乎都极度受限甚至完全丧失。从肉体层面来说，它具备它所需要的一切——强壮、敏捷、迅速。然而，我曾期望在它背后能有一个更强大的智慧。

不过，1166对少部分安保人员显示出一种奇怪的忠诚感，而那些令人作呕的家伙竟对它怀有某种同情，就像家养的狗和猫那样。这表明它的意志是可以被操控的。它有感情。它会恐惧。

我相信这是我们进步的第一个迹象。虽然承认我们的技术仍然处于初级阶段，但它为我们指明了需要努力的方向，并且证明了改进是有可能的。尽管如此，1166（「亚娜比」）仍是一个古怪有趣的小生物。它坐在角落里盯着我的样子，还有它演奏的那些滑稽小曲子（我很高兴有人认真对待了我的提议，着实让我笑了一番），都让我觉得有趣。

<Bold>结论:</>
我打算将它隔离，它只能与我接触。考虑到我在项目中的重要性，我的安全必须得到加倍的保障。而且，当它发出可怜兮兮的小声音时，我或许还能从中找到一些乐趣。

待我完成对它的训练后，我将变成它的整个世界，除此之外，它什么都不会知道。

<Bold>签名:</>
哈雷·索耶博士

Something happened, everything is upside down. There’s a hole in the room, but everything outside is so loud. There’s screaming everywhere. I’m better off in here, for now. I’ll cover the hole with something. 

It sounds like everything is quiet now. Don’t think it’s even been an hour since it all started. No one’s tried to get in here. I think I’m going to head outside. 

THERE ARE BODIES EVERYWHERE PILES AND PILES THEY LOOK LIKE ME OH GOD OH GOD WHAT’S HAPPENING 

<widget id="Line"/>

Finally calmed down. Have to be calm. Have to think clearly. Have to get out. I’m going to see if anyone is around. 

There’s a man inside the construction vehicle. I tried banging on the glass. I don’t think he can hear me, and he isn’t moving. 

Have to get back to my room where it’s safe. Figure out what happens now.
target:
房间开始移动了。我不确定这意味着什么，也不知道自己可能会去往哪里。我很害怕，但我在努力保持镇定——

有事情发生了，一切都颠倒了。房间里有个洞，但外面的一切都太吵了。到处都是尖叫声。目前我还是待在这里比较好。我会用什么东西把洞遮住。

现在听起来一切都安静了下来。距离这一切开始还不到一个小时。没有人试图闯进来。我想我要出去看看。

到处都是尸体，堆积如山，他们都长得像我，我的天哪，我的天哪，到底发生了什么

<widget id="Line"/>

终于冷静下来了。必须冷静。必须清醒地思考。必须逃出去。我要看看周围有没有人。

施工车辆里有个男人。我试着敲玻璃。我不认为他听得到我，而且他一动不动。

必须回到我的房间，那里安全。弄清楚接下来会发生什么。

source:
I couldn’t get the thought out of my head. What Stanley was implying.

I always believed they were homegrown. Maybe animals or something, but not PEOPLE. I mean, what about a giant toy with an appetite for men and women screams “Yeah, I’m a person”? 

Snooping around documents for the eggheads is a punishable offense. And if the rumors about punishments here are true, then that means being careful is a must.

But too many people have lost their lives to these things for the rest of us to be blind and accepting that we can keep them under control, and that we can trust Playtime at their word.

I’ve looked into things a little bit. I know the guys that guard the Archives Room. They keep a tight ship, but in the right setting with the right type of mood, their lips get real loose. They let slip the process and code for getting in.

While security feeds were down one night, I went in. Didn’t get very far, but I grabbed a few prisoner profile documents. The observations were from one “Dr. Harley Sawyer.” Not a name I recognize. But the observations mentioned people…

I’ll be investigating further. But I’m starting to worry that Stanley might have been onto something…
target:
我无法把这些念头从我的脑海中赶出去。斯坦利话里的暗示。

我一直以为那些东西是人为制造的。可能是动物或者别的什么东西，但绝不是人。我的意思是，一个拥有对男人和女人食欲的巨大玩具，怎么可能让人觉得「是的，这是个人」呢?

偷偷查看那些给科学家们的文件是一种会被惩罚的行为。而如果这里关于惩罚的传闻是真的，那就必须要非常小心了。

但是，已经有太多人因为这些玩意儿而丢掉了性命，我们其他人不能再盲目地相信他们能被控制住，也不能再天真地认为我们可以相信「游戏时间」的承诺了。

我已经稍微调查了一下。我认识守卫档案室的那些人。他们管得非常严，但在合适的环境与心情下，他们的嘴巴就会松很多。他们无意间透露了进入的程序与密码。

在一次夜间安保监控暂时中断时，我溜了进去。没走多远，但我抓了几份囚犯档案文件。观察记录来自某个「哈雷·索耶博士」。我不认识这个名字。但那些观察记录提到了人……

我还会继续调查。但我开始担心，斯坦利可能真的发现了些什么……

<Bold>Weekly Checkup: 1424</>

Week ending 4/21/95

<widget id="Line"/>

Subject: 1424

<widget id="Line"/>

Original Procedure Date: 01/95

<widget id="Line"/>

Reason(s) for Observation: 

- Disorganized behavior

- Thought disorder

- Confusion

- Memory loss

- Catalepsy

<widget id="Line"/>

Observations:

Subject has only fleeting moments of true awareness. Though physically capable of speech, 1424’s speech is incoherent, mumbled, and rare. Furthermore, will rarely respond to any questions or commands directly, seemingly disconnected cognitively from their surroundings.

Subject’s catatonic state is accompanied by catalepsy, a condition which causes loss of muscle coordination and a rigidity of the body. For example, when in this state, if staff raise one of the subjects limbs, subject will not lower it or even seem aware of the stimuli.

Subject will eat if food is placed directly in the mouth, and will occasionally respond if called by their birth name, though this is rare.

<widget id="Line"/>

Conclusion:

The exact cause of 1424’s symptoms remain unknown, but were present immediately following their original procedure.

[ X ] No Change
[    ] Transfer Out

<widget id="Line"/>

<Italic>To be filled by department head</>

target:
<Bold>每周检查:1424</>

截止至4/21/95

<widget id="Line"/>

对象:1424

<widget id="Line"/>

原始程序日期:01/95

<widget id="Line"/>

观察原因: 

- 行为紊乱

- 思维障碍

- 混淆

- 记忆丧失

- 紧张性昏厥

<widget id="Line"/>

观察:

对象仅在极短暂的时刻具备真正的清醒意识。虽然1424在身体上具备说话能力，但其言语不连贯、含糊不清且极为稀少。此外，很少会对任何问题或指令作出直接反应，显然在认知上与周围环境脱节。

对象的紧张性昏迷状态伴随紧张性昏厥，这会导致失去肌肉协调以及身体僵硬。举个例子，当在这种状态下，如果工作人员抬起对象的肢体，对象不会放下该肢体，甚至似乎对刺激毫无意识。

如果食物直接放进嘴里，对象会进食，并偶尔会对出生名字作出反应，但这极为少见。

<widget id="Line"/>

结论:

1424症状的确切原因仍然未知，但这些症状在原始程序执行后立即出现。

Operator,

I know this new posting is a weird one, but it’s <Underline>important</> to what’s being <Underline>built here</> (remember no talking about <Underline>any</> of that). Think of it like a promotion! After all, it’s YOU we’re entrusting to be stationed here. With the eventual additions of heating, air conditioning, working signal, and a few chairs, it might even feel downright cozy!

<Bold>You’ll notice this station is equipped with a variety of compounds labeled A, B, and C. If those come into contact with one another AND the Red Smoke, then you’d best make sure your cigarette breaks are somewhere else until the system flushes. Otherwise, your bit of relief might come at the cost of a few thousand lives.</>

I’ve left more detailed instructions for you below.

Also, I know we’ve had this conversation before, but it’s important that you NOT rip forms in half simply because you deem half the note more useful than the other. I have to believe you’re better than a barbarian monkey man, and that you can show SOME appreciation for...
target:
操作员，

我知道这个新岗位有点奇怪，但对这里正在<Underline>建设的项目</>来说，它很<Underline>重要</>(记住，不要谈论<Underline>任何</>相关内容)。把它当作一次升职吧!毕竟，我们信任你，才把你派到这里驻守。等以后供暖、空调、信号正常运作了，再加上几把椅子，这里甚至会变得相当舒适!

<Bold>你会注意到这个工作站配备了多种标记为A、B和C的化合物。如果它们彼此接触并且遇到红烟，那你最好确保抽烟休息时离得远一点，直到系统完成冲洗。否则，你的一点放松可能会导致几千条人命的代价。</>

我已在下方为你留下了更详细的指示。

另外，虽然我们之前聊过这个话题，但提醒你很重要：不能仅仅因为觉得便签的一半比另一半更有用，就把表格撕成两半。我得相信你不是个蛮荒的猴子野人，你也该表现出对规则的...些许尊重，

source:
Last week, Stanley was attacked on duty. He’s one of the nice ones down here. Even feels bad for those things. Tries his best to sneak candy and toys to them between shifts. He thinks most of us don’t notice, but we do.

The soft-hearted idiot thought he could sneak food to Boxy after hours. Just walked right into the cell. Had it not been for a few other guards stationed nearby with tranquilizers, he wouldn’t have made it out.

I visited him in the Infirmary the morning after it happened to see if he was alright. I always knew the guy was a bit of an airhead, but to walk into a cell like that? And with one of the big ones, no less? That’s just downright stupid.

I asked him why. Why risk it? What’s it to him? Why does it matter?

He was quiet for a little, like he was afraid to tell me.

“They’re not just beasts, Cole.” he finally said. “They were… MORE than that, once.”

I asked him how he could believe that.

“Been watching,” he said, “Paying attention to things. Reports. Eyeing some of the stuff the scientists pass between one another”.

After a while, I got him to keep that crazy talk to himself, and made him promise not to snoop like that again. Told him to get some sleep. But ever since our talk, I haven’t been able to get anything he said off my mind.

It can’t be true. I’ve seen what those things can do. I mean, they’re 12 feet tall for goodness sake, how can they be anything other than monsters?

It’s silly. It’s stupid. And whatever Stanley’s trying to say, he’s wrong.
target:
上周，斯坦利在值班时遭到袭击。他是这里少数的好人之一。他甚至对那些东西感到同情。他总是尽力在换班时偷偷给它们带糖果和玩具。他以为我们大多数人都没注意到，但其实我们都看在眼里。

这个心软的白痴以为可以在下班后偷偷给博克西喂食。就这么大摇大摆地走进了牢房。要不是附近有几名携带镇静剂的警卫，他可能就出不来了。

事发后的第二天早上，我去医务室看望了他，想看看他是否还好。我一直知道这家伙有点脑残，但竟然直接走进一间牢房?还是一个那么大的实验体的牢房?这也太他妈蠢了。

我问他为什么这么做。为什么要冒险?这关他什么事?为什么他在意?

他沉默了一会儿，好像害怕告诉我。

「它们不仅仅是野兽，科尔，」他最终说道，「它们曾经……不止于此。」

我问他怎么能相信那种鬼话。

「我一直在观察，」他说，「留意一些事情。报告。科学家们互相传递的一些东西。」

过了一会儿，我让他别再胡扯了，并让他保证不再偷窥那些东西。我让他去休息一下。但从那以后，我始终无法把他的话赶出脑海。

不可能是真的。我见过那些东西能做什么。我是说，它们足足有12英尺高，怎么可能是其他东西而不是怪物?

太可笑了。太愚蠢了。不管斯坦利想说什么，他错了。

source:
<Bold>CAUTION:</> 

For those involved with our construction processes, we caution your use of combustion or heat-based elements within environments containing Red Smoke. Due to the nature of its composition, when exposed to the right pressure conditions, the gas has been tested to react to high temperatures. While its use above can be regulated by environmental sensors and the correct filter equipment, the environments below are not yet afforded such luxuries (Which is why the advanced piping leading from our production center above is first on your docket). With higher natural pressure below, the matter is all the more urgent. 

We caution against the use of lighters, lanterns, and other smaller objects that produce heat. For necessary machinery, we require the use of nitrous cooling equipment to stabilize vehicle temperatures. 

As always, we wish for quick and efficient work. However we might help in this matter, simply let us know.

Our Thanks,
The Science Staff
target:
<Bold>警告:</> 

对于参与我们施工过程的人员，请注意在含有红色烟雾的环境中谨慎使用燃烧或发热元素。由于该气体成分的特性，在适当的气压条件下，经测试会对高温产生反应。虽然其在上方的使用可以通过环境传感器和正确的过滤设备来控制，但下方环境尚未拥有这些条件(这就是为什么来自我们上方生产中心的高级管道是首要任务)。由于下方的自然压力较大，问题更加紧迫。

我们提醒不要使用打火机、灯笼及其他小型发热物品。对于必要的机械设备，我们要求使用氧化氮冷却设备以稳定车辆的温度。

和往常一样，我们期望快速高效的完成工作。如果在这方面有任何我们能提供的帮助，请随时告知。

致以谢意，
科学团队

source:
Reassignment. Ol’ Cole isn’t a “Resource Extraction Specialist” anymore, he’s a “Shelf Keeper” (basically a prison guard).  

I don’t know how I should feel about that. The letter they sent me seemed nice enough, commending me for fixing their mistakes. I should be grateful, I suppose. But I know I’ll wake up tomorrow, and the reality will hit me as it has every morning since the Incident. My friends are gone. 

Dozens went in to clean up their mess, but only a handful came back. That guilt ate me up. Probably always will. 

Those of us left got a pat on the back for doing what was expected and were promptly dropped into whatever new role Playtime could find for us. Me, they put down here with them; the things that killed my friends, that would kill me too if they had their way.  

I’ve sat alone in my apartment for countless nights now, thinking it all through. The faces of my friends and my co-workers, their families, they all come to me. And in the morning, I’m there with the monsters who killed them. 

Maybe I’m exactly where I need to be. I can make sure they stay down here in the deepest, darkest hole imaginable. Right where they belong.
target:
重新分配职位。老科尔不再是「资源开采专员」了，我现在是个「货架管理员」（说白了就是狱警）。

我不知道对此该作何感想。他们发给我的信看似挺好，还赞扬我弥补了他们的错误。我想我应该感到感激。但我知道，明天醒来时，现实会像自那起事件以来的每个早晨一样袭来。我的朋友们都不在了。

几十个人进去清理他们的烂摊子，但只有少数人活着回来。那种负罪感侵蚀着我，也许永远都会。

我们这些幸存的人因为做了该做的事而得到了拍拍肩膀的嘉奖，然后就被迅速推到了玩乐时光公司给我们随便安排的新岗位上。至于我，他们把我扔到这儿，和那些东西一起；是它们杀死了我的朋友，若有机会也会杀我。

我已经在公寓里独自度过了无数个夜晚，反复想着这一切。我的朋友、同事们的脸庞，还有他们的家人，他们都会出现在我脑海里。而到了早上，我就要和那些杀害他们的怪物待在一起。

也许我正是应该待在现在的地方。我能确保它们永远待在这最深最黑的洞里。那儿正是它们该待的地方。

Once again, we continue to be in awe of your support and love for Poppy Playtime, and we cannot thank you enough for it. 
We watch the videos you make; we read and share your lore speculation; 
we celebrate each piece of fan mail you send. We would not be where we are without each and every one of you. 
You were ever present in our day to day as we built and developed Chapter 4.

We look forward to telling bolder, bigger, and stranger stories and our journey has already begun so….stay tuned for more…

Love, Always,
Mob Entertainment
target:
再次，我们对你们给予《波比的游戏时间》的支持和热爱感到惊叹，对此我们感激不尽。
我们观看了你们制作的视频；我们阅读并分享你们的剧情推测；
我们为每一封你们发来的粉丝邮件而庆祝。没有你们每一个人，我们不会走到今天这个位置。
在我们构建和开发第四章的过程中，你们一直贯穿于我们的日常生活之中。

我们期待讲述更大胆、更宏大、更奇异的故事，而且我们的旅程已经开始了……所以，敬请期待更多……

永远爱你们的，

source:
This place is a prison. I don’t know what I thought it’d be, but it wasn’t this. I mean, what did I do wrong? They made me into this, and put me in a cell. There must be hundreds, maybe even thousands of others here. How could this happen? 

There’s no food here, only the bodies, and I refuse to eat them.  

The train, that’s what takes everyone here. The conductor’s dead, but he has a key, a key that makes the train move. I don’t know if there are people elsewhere, or if they intend to come back here with more like me. I’ll take the key, make sure no one else can come here. I’ll put it where no one can find it. 

I don’t know how little or how much my life mattered, but I can do this. This one thing. Maybe it’ll save someone. Anyone. Even just one person. That would be enough. Nobody else should hear what I’ve had to hear inside this place. Nobody else should know hell like this, or the demons that live there. 

What’s important:
-That I helped someone the way I wanted to someday when I thought I was adopted.
-That my life mattered to someone. 

Why:
So that I’ll know, wherever I go now (hopefully to my parents) that I fulfilled a little of what I said I would, and made life just a little better for someone else, even if this place took everything else.
target:
这个地方是一座监狱。我不知道我原本以为它会是什么样子，但绝对不是这样的。我是说，我到底做错了什么?他们把我变成这样，然后把我关进了一个牢房。这里肯定有成百上千，甚至上万的其他人。这是怎么发生的?

这里没有食物，只有尸体，而我拒绝吃他们。

火车，就是它把所有人带到这里来的。列车长已经死了，但他有一把钥匙，一把能让火车移动的钥匙。我不知道其他地方是否还有人，或者他们是否打算带着更多像我这样的人回来。我要拿走那把钥匙，确保再也不会有人被带到这里来。我会把它藏在一个没人能找到的地方。

我不知道我的生命究竟有多大的意义，但我可以做这件事。唯一的一件事。也许这样能拯救某个人。任何一个人。甚至仅仅是一个人。那就足够了。不应该再有人听到我在这个地方听到过的声音。不应该再有人体会过这样的地狱，以及住在这里的恶魔。

重要的是:
-我曾经希望有人能在某天用我想要的方式帮我一把，就像我以为自己被收养时那样。
-我的生命对某个人来说是重要的。

为什么:
这样一来，无论我现在去了哪里(希望是回到我父母那里)，我都会知道，我实现了自己说过的一点点誓言，给别人的生活带来了些许改善，哪怕这个地方夺走了一切。

source:
It happened again. The experiments broke free.

I don’t remember much. All the doors opened, and I was pinned to the floor by something big. Everything went black.

I woke up in one of the same cells the experiments were in. I could hear other guards next to me. Above me. They were screaming, pleading.
 
It reminded me of the experiments. The way they’d smash against the walls, bearing their teeth and trying to act like they weren’t afraid.

It’s funny that I haven’t thought of home yet, locked in this cell. Honestly, I haven’t thought of home in a long time. That was another life, another me. No, the only thought that comes to mind now is how inevitable this all was.

They hurt us, and we hurt them back. We hurt them, and they hurt us in return. Over years and years and countless incidents, this is the way it’s been. Nobody cares to stop it, and nobody’s innocent anymore. We MADE them, and they’ve made US. We’ve been prisoners to a cycle down here in the dark, and I don’t think <Italic>any</> of us deserve to see the light anymore.

If you ever find these notes, please, whoever you are, never let another hell like this exist. Otherwise, it’ll consume you and ALL your good intentions.

If you ask me, all of us, we’re in the deepest, darkest hole imaginable. Right where we belong.
target:
又发生了。实验体逃脱了。

我记不太清了。所有的门都打开了，有个巨大的东西把我压在了地板上。然后一切陷入黑暗。

我醒来时，发现自己被困在实验体待过的那种牢房里。我能听见旁边和其他地方的守卫在尖叫、哀求。

这让我想起了那些实验体。它们会撞击墙壁，龇牙咧嘴地假装自己不害怕。

说来有趣，在这个牢房里，我竟然还没有想起过家。说实话，我已经很久没想过家了。那是另一个人生，另一个我。如今，唯一浮现在脑海中的念头是这一切的不可避免性。

它们伤害我们，我们反过来伤害它们。我们伤害它们，它们反过来伤害我们。多年的时间、无数的事件都证明了这一点。没人试图阻止这一切，也没人是无辜的了。它们是我们制造出来的，它们也塑造了我们。在这黑暗之中，我们都被困在一个循环里，我想 <Italic>所有</> 人，都不配再见到光明了。

如果你发现了这些笔记，那么不管你是谁，请永远别让这样的地狱重现。否则它会吞噬你，吞噬你所有的善意。

依我看，我们所有人都身处一个可以想象到的最深、最黑暗的坑中。这就是我们应得的位置。

source:
<Bold>Project Goals:</>
Create a reinforced, easily defensible central location for Security staff, equipped with blast doors, defenses, and multiple emergency entrances/exits.

<Bold>Project Objectives:</>
- Design and implement an independent electrical network, including an on-site generator.
- Wire a series of high-voltage electrical coils into the network, capable of deterring intruders.
- Install reinforced blast doors capable of withstanding external pressure greater than 50 PSI.
- Construct 3-4 exterior pathways, each with reinforced doorways and failsafes.
- (<Italic>Secondarily</>) Construct a discreet emergency elevator system capable of transporting key personnel from upper floors.

<Bold>Project Timeline:</> 
10-12 Months

<Bold>Potential Limitations/Setbacks:</>
Misprioritization of overall Prison construction (needs further clarity)
Worksite hazards
Budget Constraints
target:
<Bold>项目目标:</>
为安全人员创建一个加固且易于防御的中心位置，配备防爆门、防御设施以及多个紧急出入口。

<Bold>项目目的:</>
- 设计并实施一个独立的电力网络，包括现场发电机。
- 将一系列高压电圈连接到网络中，能够起到威慑入侵者的作用。
- 安装加固型防爆门，能够承受大于50 PSI的外部压力。
- 建造3-4条外部通道，每条通道都配备加固型门和故障保护装置。
- (<Italic>次要目标</>) 建造一个隐蔽的紧急电梯系统，能够从上层运输关键人员。

<Bold>项目时间表:</> 
10-12个月

source:
First week at Playcare. I didn’t know what to expect. I didn’t know what I wanted it to be. There are a lot of people here, and they’ve given a lot to me. A room, a roof, a big pink bed, girly toys (I’m a little too old for that), and a journal. The adults encourage me to talk to the other kids, but I’m not sure what to say to them. Most of them have been here almost their whole lives, or, at least, they were young enough that they can’t remember what they lost. My parents loved, protected, and taught me, and I’m not sure the others even remember what that’s like. They don’t know what they don’t have, but I do. I remember a lot. I try to be kind to them though, even if there’s very little I can say. Right now, I think I prefer it like that. 

The nice counselor who said I was quiet told me that I could say whatever I wanted in my journal, and it would only be for me. Make two lists, she said, one with what’s important to me right now, in this moment, and the other being why. She said it might help me. I’m going to try it. 

What’s important to me: 
- That the nice counselor cares enough about me to try to make me feel at home.
- Trying to get comfortable here. Even if it’s not home, it’s all I have now.
- That my life matters, since it can be lost so quickly.
- That my parents’ lives mattered too. 

Why:
Because I’m scared. Anything can happen in an instant and leave you with nothing, and because of that, I’m scared that nothing matters. But I want to feel happy again (Really, I do), and it’s important to me right now, in this moment, that someone here cares that I feel at home, even if I’m not.
target:
在Playcare的第一周。我不知道该期待什么，也不知道我希望它是什么样子。这里有很多人，他们给了我很多东西。一个房间，一个屋顶，一张粉色的大床，女孩子玩的玩具(我有点太老了)，还有一本日记。大人们鼓励我和其他孩子说话，但我不知道该对他们说什么。他们大多数几乎一生都在这里，或者至少他们还很小，小到记不清自己失去了什么。我的父母曾经爱我、保护我、教导我，我不确定其他孩子是否还记得那样的生活是什么样子。他们不知道自己缺少什么，但我知道。我记得很多。尽管如此，我仍然尝试对他们友善，哪怕我没什么话可说。现在，我觉得我更喜欢这样。

那位说我安静的好心辅导员告诉我，我可以在日记里写任何想写的东西，这本日记只属于我。她说让我列两个清单，一个是我现在此刻认为重要的事情，另一个是为什么。她说这可能会对我有所帮助。我打算试试。

对我来说重要的事情:
- 那位善良的辅导员关心我，并努力让我感到像在家里一样。
- 试着在这里过得舒服一点。即便这里不是家，它现在是我唯一拥有的。
- 我的生命很重要，因为它可能在瞬间失去。
- 我父母的生命也同样重要。

为什么:
因为我害怕。任何事情都可能在一瞬间发生，让你一无所有，正因为如此，我害怕什么都不重要。但我想再次感到快乐(我真的想)，现在此刻对我来说最重要的，是有个人在意我是否在这里感到如同在家，即使我实际上并不在这里。

source: A resent for what brought us here.
target: 对我们到此缘由的怨恨。

source:
This wasn’t what I thought, what ANYONE thought. They took me somewhere. Not out, but under. Deep beneath EVERYTHING. They gave me a shot, and I went to sleep. Maybe that was days ago. Maybe it was weeks. I remember images. My skin opened up like flower petals, a man who looked like a doctor digging around inside me, taking things out. I remember feeling his touch through my ribs and into the back of my spine. I remember hearing a snap. Everywhere was red.  

When I woke up, everything hurt, so I screamed. Hours and hours of screaming. I stopped once I knew no one was listening.  

I’m not me anymore. My body is not my body. My hands are not my hands. I try to brush the hair I still feel at my shoulders, and touch nothing. I can’t separate my fingers, even though I can almost feel them move. It’s like nothing of what I feel actually is. Maybe that’s been true for a while now.  

I’m in a room that isn’t so different from the one I had in the orphanage. Everything’s nailed down. I’ve been here a long time. 

I’m trying to write the lists that helped before, but I’ve dropped the pen three times. I don’t know what else to do. 

Why did I survive if this was all I’d get? What did it all mean if this is where it put me? This can’t be all there is.  

What’s important to me:
-Waking up from this nightmare.
-Getting out.
-Getting back to being me.

Why:
Because I’d started to like life again before, and none of this should be real.
target:
这不是我所想的，也不是任何人所想的。他们把我带到了某个地方。不是外面，而是地下。深埋在一切之下。他们给我打了一针，我就睡着了。也许那是几天前的事，也许是几周前。我记得一些画面。我的皮肤像花瓣一样绽开，一个像博士的男人在我身体里翻找，取出东西。我记得感觉到他的触碰穿过我的肋骨，深入脊柱后部。我记得听到「咔嚓」一声。到处都是红色。

 当我醒来时，全身都疼，于是我开始尖叫。尖叫了数小时又数小时。意识到没人会听见后，我停止了尖叫。

 我不再是原来的我了。我的身体不再属于我。我的手也不再是我的手。我试图拨弄肩膀上仍然感觉存在的头发，却碰不到什么。尽管我能隐约感到手指在动，却无法将它们分开。我所感受到的一切似乎都不是真实的。也许这种情况已经持续了一段时间。

 我的房间和我在孤儿院的那间没什么不同。所有东西都被钉得死死的。我已经在这里待了很久很久。

 我正试图列出以前曾有所帮助的清单，但已经三次掉笔了。我不知道还能做什么。

 如果我只能得到这些，为什么能活下来?如果这一切就是终点，这一切的一切到底意味着什么?这不可能就是全部。

 对我重要的事:

-从这场噩梦中醒来。

-逃出去。

-重新找回自我。

 为什么:

因为在这一切之前，我已经开始重新喜欢生活了，而现在这一切都不应该是真的。

source:
Harley,

Let me begin this with a bit of bluntness, as I know you appreciate not dancing around what needs to be said. Despite how much it pains me, I’ve decided to remove you from the <Bold>Young Geniuses Program</>.

I didn’t want it to turn out this way, Harley. I didn’t want to hurt or discourage you. Yours is truly a brilliant mind, probably the most brilliant of anyone I’ve ever known. Every day I’ve seen your drive, your determination, and your incessant need for progress. Working with you, it’s been one of the most rewarding experiences of my entire life. But even so, I have to be honest with myself, and with you. Because despite all that I see in you, despite all that you could be, there’s one glaring flaw in you I can no longer make myself ignore. 

Your lack of humility.

Scientific progress should ALWAYS be to the benefit of humanity. Progress made simply for the sake of progress often winds up hurting us more than it helps. I’ve tried to temper that in you as I once had to temper it in myself, but it became clear to me that such intrusions on my part only incited your anger. You finally lashed out at me one evening and stormed out of the lab. “Don’t be soft, Elliot.” you said, “Progress doesn’t care for how anyone feels about it.” I knew immediately that you were wrong, but I wasn’t sure what to do–what could shift your thinking.

In agonizing over it, I was reminded of what ultimately changed me. Of what gave me the perspective I needed. It was seeing the world and people again, bouncing back from rejection and hardship through connection. 

In thinking about those days, I'm reminded that rejection can sometimes be the best thing for us. It can remind us why our actions matter, and who they’re for. Ultimately, I believe it made me a better person, and I have to believe that doing this now will make you better too. So I challenge you to head for home, Harley, and to look at the people around you. To try for a new perspective. To better know why progress matters.

One day, I hope you’ll understand. Maybe you’ll even thank me. But even still, I’m sorry.

Your Friend,
Elliot Ludwig
target:
哈雷，

让我开门见山地说吧，因为我知道你不喜欢拐弯抹角。尽管这让我非常痛苦，但我还是决定将你从<Bold>青年天才计划</Bold>中除名。

我不想事情变成这样，哈雷。我不想伤害你，也不想让你灰心。你的头脑真的非常聪明，可能是我认识的所有人中最聪明的。每天，我都能看到你的动力、决心以及对进步的不懈追求。与你一起工作，是我一生中最值得的经历之一。然而即便如此，我必须对自己诚实，也必须对你诚实。因为尽管我在你身上看到了很多优点，尽管你潜力无限，但有一个致命的缺陷，我再也无法忽视。

你缺乏谦逊。

科学进步应该始终以造福人类为目的。单纯为了进步而取得的进展，往往最终带来的伤害远大于帮助。我曾经试图纠正你这一点，就像我过去不得不纠正自己一样，但我的干预显然只会激起你的愤怒。有一天晚上，你终于对我发火，然后冲出了实验室。「别优柔寡断了，艾略特。」 你说，「进步才不在乎谁对它有什么感觉。」 我立刻知道你是错的，但我不确定该怎么办，该如何让你转变思想。

在苦苦思索中，我回忆起最终改变了我的因素。是什么让我获得了应有的视角。那是重新认识世界和人们的过程，通过与他人建立联系，从拒绝和困境中反弹回来。

在回顾那些日子时，我明白拒绝有时对我们而言是最好的事情。它可以提醒我们为什么行动重要，以及我们行动的目标人群是谁。最终，我相信这些经历让我成为了一个更好的人，而我也必须相信，我现在所做的会让你变得更好。所以我希望你回到家，哈雷，去观察你周围的人。试着获取一个新的视角，更好地理解为什么进步重要。

我希望有一天你能理解。也许你甚至会感谢我。但即便如此，我还是感到抱歉。

你的朋友，
艾略特·路德维希

source:
A very small percentage of people may experience epileptic seizures when exposed to certain visual stimuli, including flashing lights or certain patterns that may appear in videogames. Even people with no personal or family history of seizures or epilepsy may have an undiagnosed condition that can cause seizures while watching or playing videogames. Symptoms of this condition can include light-headedness, vertigo, dizziness, altered vision, eye or muscles twitches, jerking or shaking of arms or legs, involuntary movement, disorientation, confusion, momentary loss of awareness, loss of consciousness, or convulsions. These symptoms can lead to severe injury.

Immediately stop playing and consult a physician if you experience any of these symptoms; do not recommence playing until you receive approval from your physician.

Parents should watch for and ask their children about these symptoms-children and teenagers are more likely than adults to experience seizures. The risk of seizures may be reduced by taking the following precautions: do not sit too close to the screen; do not play on large screens; play in a well-lit room; do not play when drowsy or fatigued; do not play for extended periods of time; take frequent breaks (at least 15 minutes every hour). If you or any of your relatives have a history of seizures or epilepsy, consult a physician before playing or watching videogames.
target:
极少数人在接触某些视觉刺激时可能会出现癫痫发作，包括闪光灯或视频游戏中可能出现的特定图案。即使是那些没有个人或家族癫痫史的人，也可能患有未确诊的疾病，这类疾病可能在观看或玩游戏时引发癫痫。这种疾病的症状包括：头昏、眩晕、头晕、视觉变化、眼部或肌肉抽搐、手臂或腿部的抽动或晃动、非自主运动、迷惑、定向障碍、短暂意识丧失、意识丧失或癫痫发作。这些症状可能会导致严重伤害。

一旦你经历了这些症状，请立即停止游戏，并咨询医生；在获得医生许可前不要重新开始游戏。

父母应观察并询问孩子是否有此类症状——儿童和青少年比成年人更容易发生癫痫发作。可以通过以下预防措施减少癫痫发作的风险：不要离屏幕太近；不在大屏幕上游戏；在光线充足的房间里玩；不要在昏昏欲睡或疲惫时玩；不要长时间玩游戏；定期休息(至少每小时15分钟)。如果你或你的任何亲属有癫痫病史，在玩或观看视频游戏前，请咨询医生。
